                <p><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><b><span class="spnMessageText"><a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&id=6391" title="View Skeleric's Profile" onMouseOver="(window.status='View Skeleric\'s Profile'); return true" onMouseOut="(window.status=''); return true">Skeleric</a></span></b></font><br />
                <font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Zombie</small></font><br />
                <td bgcolor="#ECECEC" width="100%" colspan="2" valign="top">
                  <table width="100%" height="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top">
                      <img src="images/icon_mi_1.gif" width="15" height="15" border="0" alt="" title="" hspace="3" /><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;08/20/2003&nbsp;:&nbsp; 2:59:49 PM</font>
                      &nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&id=6391"><img src="images/icon_profile.gif" width="15" height="15" border="0" alt="Show Profile" title="Show Profile" align="absmiddle" hspace="6" /></a>
                      &nbsp;<a href="http://lotgd.net/" target="_blank"><img src="images/icon_homepage.gif" width="15" height="15" border="0" alt="Visit Skeleric's Homepage" title="Visit Skeleric's Homepage" align="absmiddle" hspace="6" /></a>
                      <hr noshade size="2"></td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
           	<td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000">
                      <font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> I don't know why, but reading that druid AA post made me want to share the vision that *I* had for horses way back when I heard they were going to be introduced.  This post is long winded, and completely pointless, but just a novel look back at what I think was done wrong with horses.<br /><br />Horses are not merely an upgrade to speed and meditation.  Not in real life, nor fantasy.  For a warrior, a horse is a weapon, it makes them harder to attack, and it fights with them.  For a caster, a horse would provide them the protection of lifting them above the battle.  For both sides, it would also provide additional carrying capacity.<br /><br />So here's how you could have represented this in Everquest.  Horses are attached to items that when equipped, you are on your mount.  Melee get horses that attack with them, they equip their mounts in either hand, as a weapon, it has attack stats and such, they give up a weapon though because they are controlling the reigns.  Knights (Pal, SK) can equip their horse in their off hand, as the only off hand weapon available to them.  They do this at the expense of their shield.  The attacks from the horse check against the owner's horsemanship skill.<br /><br />Casters get horses which do not have melee stats (though perhaps there are some melee horses available to casters), but rather stats to help them as a caster.<br /><br />There is a horsemanship skill.  As you go up in it, your horse will become a bit faster, and melee will attack better with it.  Also you will start and stop more quickly (early on, the horse is difficult to start or stop).  <br /><br />As you gain levels of horsemanship, you can try various special moves whose success checks against your level. Examples:<br />"Burst Run" which is a 30 minute reuse which improves your movement rate by 15% for 1 minute, or <br />"Rearing Attack" which is a 2 minute reuse which significantly increases your chance to critical with your next horse hit, or <br />"Prancing Pony" which is a 15 minute reuse move that makes you harder to hit for 30 seconds, while also removing you from the ability to melee<br /><br />You obtain these special horse moves at certain levels (ala monk kicks), and your chance to succeed at the move depends on your horsemanship skill.<br /><br />Horse speed is determined by a combination of the quality of the steed and the skill of the rider.  <br /><br />Knights (Pal SK) get an AA to permit them to equip their horse in their range or ammo slot, and regain the use of their shield or the ability to equip a 2 hand weapon.  They can only do this if it is a horse which has that slot as an option (Horse, Slot: Primary, Secondary, Range).  The roleplay reason for this is that some horses can be guided with the legs only, freeing up both hands, but only the best horses are trained in this way.  When equipped in range, the knight cannot use the horse as a weapon, but does gain any other available stats.<br /><br />The horsemanship skill increases slowly as you ride around.  Those who melee with a horse check on the skill as well, and their horse skill will go up faster as a result (they are much more in tune with their horse's abilities).<br /><br />Balancing horses becomes easy, they are balanced in the same way as all other gear, they are just a regular piece of equipment with one additional advantage: speed, which comes at the price of slightly reduced other stats (compared to comparable other gear for the same slot).<br /><br />Some special attacks, such as monk kicks, and rogue back stabs are not available from horse back.  Also, sneak, hide, and a variety of other moves are not possible from horseback.<br /><br />Being on a horse would increase the distance from which you can attack with regular melee.<br /><br />For the protection from battle aspect, all horses have some AC on them.  Better (bigger, tougher, smarter) horses have better AC.  Given what they've done with charms, they could even have increased AC or agility based on how good your horsemanship skill is.<br /><br />You cannot mount or unmount a horse for 15-30 seconds after having been involved in a battle (or last equipping/unequipping your horse) to give the animal some time to calm down.<br /><br />*this* should be what horses are, not the one-dimensional things that they are in the game now.<br /><br />/rant off.</span id="msg"></font>
           	</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="bottom"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> <img src="images/jump2refection_125.gif" border="0" alt="" title="" align="middle" />-Skeleric<br />Author of Legend of the Green Dragon: <a href="http://lotgd.net" target="_blank">http://lotgd.net</a></span></font></td>
